---
import Layout from '../layouts/Layout.astro';
---

<Layout title="About | Amid the Noise">
  <section class="section about-hero">
    <h1>About</h1>
    <div class="about-grid">
      <div class="about-text">
        <p>
          I’m Matthew McClendon, a San Francisco–based designer, technologist,
          writer, and father.
        </p>
        <p>
          For most of my career, I have worked in systems where the interface is
          only the surface. Underneath it, something more consequential is
          happening: a model is scoring, a workflow is routing, a signal is
          being interpreted, or a decision is being made under uncertainty.
        </p>
        <p>
          That is the work that holds my attention. I care about products and
          systems that have to earn trust, not assume it.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="about-image-wrap">
        <img
          class="about-image"
          src="/official-profile-1024x.png"
          alt="Matthew McClendon profile portrait"
        />
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="section">
    <h2>What Amid the Noise is for</h2>
    <p>
      <em>Amid the Noise</em> is where I write through the patterns that keep
      returning. Trust. Signal. Judgment. The human consequences of systems
      that act before anyone has a chance to explain what just happened.
    </p>
    <p>
      Some of that writing is professional by design. It helps recruiters,
      hiring managers, and collaborators understand the kind of problems I am
      built for. Some of it is broader and more reflective. I am interested in
      how people and systems shape each other, and in what it takes to preserve
      clarity when complexity starts to sprawl.
    </p>
    <p>
      The site is not meant to be a feed. It is meant to be a body of work.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section class="section">
    <h2>How I work</h2>
    <p>
      I tend to do my best work where stakes are real and behavior is hard to
      read at a glance. AI-assisted products. Decision systems. Financial and
      operational environments where a clean interface is not enough because the
      real question is whether the system can be understood, challenged, and
      trusted.
    </p>
    <p>
      My background spans early internet platforms, enterprise systems,
      financial workflows, and AI-native environments. Across all of them, the
      recurring problem is familiar: how do you make invisible system behavior
      legible enough for a human being to respond with sound judgment?
    </p>
    <p>
      I care about explainability, oversight, escalation paths, and the design
      of feedback loops that help people stay oriented when the machine has more
      speed than context.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section class="section">
    <h2>A little more personally</h2>
    <p>
      I have spent enough years around technology to know that novelty is not
      the same thing as progress. I still love the craft. I still love the
      systems thinking. I still get excited by elegant infrastructure, by good
      tools, by the moment a hard problem becomes briefly clear.
    </p>
    <p>
      I am also a writer by instinct. Part of that comes from observation. Part
      of it comes from survival. Part of it probably comes from spending a life
      admiring people like Mark Twain, who understood that wit is often just
      truth arriving with better timing.
    </p>
    <p>
      I live in San Francisco. I think like a technologist, write like someone
      trying to stay honest, and care a great deal about the kind of world our
      systems are teaching people to inhabit.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section class="section">
    <h2>Focus</h2>
    <p>
      AI-native product design, trust and safety, explainability,
      human-in-the-loop systems, decision workflows, signal integrity, and the
      design of products that need to remain accountable under pressure.
    </p>
  </section>
</Layout>

<style>
  .about-grid {
    display: grid;
    grid-template-columns: minmax(0, 1fr) 260px;
    gap: 56px;
    align-items: start;
  }

  .about-text {
    min-width: 0;
  }

  .about-image-wrap {
    justify-self: end;
    width: 100%;
    max-width: 260px;
    margin-top: 0;
  }

  .about-image {
    display: block;
    width: 100%;
    height: auto;
    border: 1px solid var(--line);
    background: var(--bg);
  }

  @media (max-width: 900px) {
    .about-grid {
      grid-template-columns: 1fr;
      gap: 24px;
    }

    .about-image-wrap {
      justify-self: start;
      max-width: 220px;
      margin-top: 0;
    }
  }
</style>